20/01 7:23:48 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Personal Attack Policy-Discussion Thread</span><hr size=1> I think the inability to change posts after the fact in R&amp;R would be a good change. Editing can always be done during preview of post prior to hitting that Add Reply. Once the post is made in R&amp;R it should stand. <br>
<br>
If you really believe the issue of accountability is a large concern to the community perhaps another forum (read only) could be established for viewing potential deletions and soliciting public opinion (to be expressed in another forum specifically for that).<br>
Moderator comments could be added to or posted in the same forum as the possible deletions, explaining or providing additional information for the action.<br>
<br>
The forum for expressing opinions about impending deletions could be set the same as R&amp;R, no deletions or editing of a post after it has been made. This might encourage people to choose their words more carefully. <br>
<br>
Most important, I think, is that people feel comfortable expressing themselves and exchanging ideas and information without worrying about being attacked on a personal level. Everyone has an opinion and is welcome to express it in a manner acceptable to the community. Anyone who has difficulty understanding this concept doesn't understand the distinction between a private board run by individuals volunteering their time and energy for the collective good, and free speech. <br>
<br>
As one poster commented, we saw how far the concept of &quot;Free Lanys&quot; went when it was so boldly announced. That's the great thing about the internet in this day and age, many things are available for free - requiring only time and effort. If some individuals are unhappy by the restrictions placed on them by this community, they are always free to exercise their right to free speech another place. <br>
<br>
Take the time and effort to create your own board, put links up and enjoy the anarchy. You won't have to worry about me coming over there and trying to enforce our community standards on you. If you aren't part of the community, you don't matter. As I've heard it said many times, If you ain't part of the solution, you're part of the problem.  <br>
<br>
Anyone who has administered an open board, or moderated forums, knows you can never quiet all the critics. Just like with traffic on the streets however, board traffic must also be regulated for the good of the community. Just my 2cp. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uvanamar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vanamar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Whore</span><br> <font color=#000033>(12/20/01 7:27:04 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.unbeliever.net/images/everquest/sigs/minisig.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Personal Attack Policy-Discussion Thread</span><hr size=1> I *really* Like the no editing idea in RNR. <p><p align="center"><map name="FPMap0">
